task.summary: Default task

voice totaller work
- checked any errors with new method of voice totalling using the mid-measure barline testcase, which is what the totaller was put in for in the first place - test now passes, issue fix #165

partial measure work
- added a list to voice which keeps track of all the note durations in the voice - need to figure out how to use this - work on issue #116

partial measure work
- handling for singular notes in measure works - handling for a measure containing halves of starter measure (e.g c'2 c'4 c'8 etc) - work toward issue #116 - moved tests that pass or don't fail too hard into relevant folders (02e is in ignored due to issue #175, but chorded testcase works just fine)

partial measure work
- handling the same note works: confirmed this with another test - created expected outputs for 2 of the tests - issue fix #116 - 46d is not fixed yet issue #177 because measure x1 should come after measure 1, but gets put at the end because it's not a string

wrap up to partial measures
- added ordering method which pulls out integers and strings, sorts them both then figures out where in the resulting list the strings should fit in: issue fix #177 - testcase 46d now passes without having to use the hacky "cadenza" method, not sure whether this will be necessary in the future but anyhow - issue fix #178 and thus, issue fix #179

work toward voice navigation
- testcase 46e passes: going to do a check on the other multivoice tests to see what happens now (think most of them are in ignored) - issue fix #180, note is now under the approriate note

work toward tab fixing
- issue fix #164: changed to use 2 booleans which are checked when a measure is closed

issue fix #159
- switched CheckIfTabStaff to check 2 bools instead of every measure - removed part if drum or tab found - kept exception and added a couple of tests to check the results

initial commit for issue #59
Added a new file for anything relating to playing with SQLite libraries
work toward issue #59

restarted second objective
- cleared out old files: as I'm using a new structure most of the code from those is now irrelevant, and it's all in source code control if I need it back - started creating tests based on the key elements of data mentioned in issue #182 - work toward issue #66

added more tests and functionality to metadata browser
- created 2 new tables - instruments and instrument_pieces_join: doing it this way because of the many to many relationship between the two, but also so that later we can create other relationships between instruments such as their transpositions and instrument groupings - implemented further tests such as get by filename and get by instrument name - work toward issue #66

added more tests and functionality to metadata browser
- created 2 new tables - composers and composer_piece_join - created these again because of many to many, but also because composer table can then store information about composer's birth and death which we could then do some figuring out from another table, like "periods" to work out what time period their music exists in - added code for selecting pieces based on composer and title - work toward issue #66

added more tests and functionality to metadata browser
- created 2 new tables - keys and key_piece_join - key information will be the same *forever*, so it makes sense to chuck it in the database so we pretty much don't have to think about it again. - implemented input by fifths and mode, and retrieval by key name - this is useful because that way we don't have to manipulate the data coming in from MusicXML to figure out what key to associate with the file, and it's unlikely that a user will want to search by the number of fifths or the mode, tho we could always put that in? - work toward issue #66

added more tests and functionality to metadata browser
- added another test which should test the system collecting pieces which contain 2 diff instruments - added docstrings to every method in DataLayer explaining what each one does and what the params/return values are - work toward issue #66

modified the table setup
- switched all the tables to use CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS on first setup: alleviates using 2 queries to do 1 job - switched the ID methods to use just 2 params rather than 3 (name, cursor) as the connection object is never used - work on issue #66

more data browsing
- added functionality for adding multiple instruments - added functionality for getting multiple instruments - working on combining multi instruments with screening pieces to see if they contain both instruments - work toward issue #66

modified how composers are saved
- removed composer_piece_join table which wasn't necessary - changed queries to reflect this + tests - work toward issue #66

fixed multi-instrument browser
- fixed the method that searches for multiple instruments in 1 piece so that the query handles this rather than doing data manipulation. Doesn't look massively tidy but does the job and should be extendible no matter how many instruments are in the list. - work toward issue #66
removed single instrument method as it's not necessary

added multi-instrument multi-key method
- added new method which takes in pairings of instruments and keys and finds all the pieces containing all of the instruments in specified keys - added relevant tests, including tests to check it doesn't just return all the data and tests where it should return more than one value - work toward issue #66

changed add method to allow multiple keys
- changed all inputs of keys in tests to be instrument name followed by a list of dictionaries - changed the add method to match so that it now loops the keys adding each one in the join table

changed clef and key search methods to allow multiples
- changed clef and key methods to be basically the same logic as instrument searching so that they allow the user to search for a piece containing a list of clefs or list of keys, rather than just allowing them to use one - work toward issue #66

added advanced clef searching method
- added ability to search by clef attached to a particular instrument - added if statement around get<value>Id method return statements to stop exceptions occuring where no results are found - work toward issue #66

added further tests
- added AddTests for instruments, keys, clefs which do queries themselves and check it against the expected result - work toward issue #66

switched time sig tables to use 2 like everything else
- not really sure the benefits of using 1 or 2, just seems neater to keep it like this.

implemented adding tempos
- implemented several tests which check it's possible to add two different types of tempos (beat=beats-per-minute and beat=secondTypeOfBeat) - implemented addition in addPiece and the new tables necessary in the constructor - work toward issue #66

implemented finding by tempo
- implemented getPieceByTempo method which passes all the remaining tests in testDataLayer - think this is all done now, but should probably implement OR methods whereby we look for pieces if they contain "this" or "that" - this should be simply creating a method which calls the methods we already have but splitting the list up then combining the result. - work toward issue #66

modified tempo addition and call back
- tempo beats will usually be their string representations from mxml, so no longer need to do a conversion - however, did add a converter for english to american note names because mxml tends to use american, but it would be useful to be able to search by either - work toward #66

added more tempo tests
- added a test for 16th (here we should do some funky for loops to get it to calculate the size because storing things less than eighth seems silly as you could have unlimited uses of the sequence "hemi demi semi" - added a test for dotted notes

added find all info method
- added a method which finds all the info accross all tables for a particular file. Doesn't currently apply instrument names to keys and clefs so will need further testing/work before it's useful. Also need to take out the return values of "id" and "composer_id" because a user doesn't need to know this info and therefore it's best to keep that to data-level only. - added test for this method - work toward issue #66

added further tests for find info method
- added key test for find info method - removed indexes "id" and "composer_id" - work toward issue #66

changes to getAllPieceInfo
- changed keys and clefs so that they are properly organised by instrument - cleaned up getAllPieceInfo so that it calls methods for most of the info it's collecting, as all the queries could be potentially useful later. - work toward issue #66

changes to getPieceByTempo
- added handling for searching by hemi/demi/semi quavers - added handling for dotted notes - issue fix #66

added transpositions
- changed input of instruments to be dictionaries, which can optionally contain a "name" and a transposition ID. If no transposition ID all transposition elements in the db are set to 0 - added a test to confirm this works - need to add a test for pulling instruments out by their transpositions, then for pulling pieces out by instruments with that transposition - work toward issue #66

added search by transposition
- added method to create new instruments not attached to pieces and to search for instruments with the same transposition - work toward issue #66

further work to search by transposition
- added method to find instruments with the same transposition as the one given - this searches the table for the item and searches the table again by the item's transposition in one query - work toward issue #66

further work to search by transposition
- added method to search for all pieces containing first a particular instrument, then by that instrument or other instruments which are of the same transposition: this won't give preferential treatment to either option, but this isn't a problem because ultimately, if a piece exists containing a violin, flute, sax and trumpet and you're looking for something containing a flute, it doesn't matter whether the system finds it because a violin is in the piece. - also not sure whether searches should return just a file list or a list of all info, but I've provided a method which does the latter for a given filename so I guess it doesn't really matter. - issue fix #66

changes to datalayer
- added a new method and tests for finding a generic list of all files in the db, ready for issue #185 - removed old object SearchLoad.py and some other code that's unnecessary/from someone else's repo

created unzipper
- created unzipper in stages using unit tests: issue fix #184 - put in file musicManager which should encapsulate this and the comparator for file lists to db lists

created folderBrowser
- created a class which collates a file dict from a given folder of 2 indexes - xml and mxl files - also provided 2 methods which take this method and figure out from a given list of files in the db which are old in the db and which are new to the db - created tests to match - work toward issue #185

update to folderbrowser
- added a method which collates all the old files and all the new files into one dictionary. made this to avoid calling getFolderFiles twice which is probably inefficient - added test to confirm functionality of this new method - issue fix #185

initial musicManager class
- created testclass and music manager class - work toward issue #189

issue fix #189
- think the music manager class has progressed far enough to close this issue: the next steps are to create 2 further blocks - the parser, mentioned in issue #186, and another method in the data layer which deletes or marks files as archived.
initial commit for issue #186

handling for parts
- added handler and tests for part-names - work toward issue #186

handling for clefs and keys
- added handler and tests for clefs and keys - these work pretty much the same way and could be merged into the same method, but only for simplification I'll leave as is for now - work toward issue #186

handling for meters, tests for meters and tempos
work toward issue #186

work toward issue #186
